or their own ends, increasingly drawing the real and the recorded further apart. While this administrative sleight of hand increased the company’s reach and power within the Empire, it also bolstered profoundly new orientations to language, writing, memory, and pedagogy for the officers and Indian subordinates involved. Immersed in a subterranean world of delinquent scribes, translators, village accountants, and entrepreneurial fixers, Document Raj maps the shifting boundaries of the legible and illegible, the legal and illegitimate, that would usher India into the modern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAccountingzIndiazTamil NaduxHistoryy19th century. 0aBureaucracyzIndiazTamil NaduxHistoryy19th century. 0aDocumentationzIndiazTamil NaduxHistoryy19th century. 0aPublic administrationzIndiazTamil NaduxHistoryy19th century. 0aScribeszIndiazTamil NaduxHistoryy19th century. 0aTamil languagexWritingxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226703299423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226703299/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles